equation_narrative.headline: Exposed acidic position resolved through local sequence context and D-specific prediction channels
equation_narrative.story: Position 52 in ubiquitin sits in an exposed loop region (GKQLE[D]GRTLS) where the model must distinguish between acidic residues. Through layers 1-23, the representation shifts from generic polar/small residues (S peaks at 23% at L0) through charged character (K dominates L8-9 at 36%), finally settling into a polar/acidic profile by L23. The decision crystallizes at L24 when D overtakes T, driven by strong D-specific MLP neurons and prediction features. By L29, D reaches 49% and surges to 88% through L30-33 as multiple high-projection neurons (N31:2506 at 1.22, N32:1334 at 1.14) and features (F33:3227 at 116.5 proj) lock in the acidic identity.

perception_phase.summary: The model reads 4 structural contacts and 1 co-evolving position, assembling a representation of an exposed, flexible position. Early layers (L1-9) show volatile logit-lens outputs cycling through S→Y→H→L→T→R→K, reflecting the model's exploration of local sequence patterns rather than predictions. The K peak at L8 (36%) corresponds to reading the adjacent K at position 48 through local attention. By L13-23, the representation stabilizes around polar/small residues (S holds 13-14%, T peaks at 19% at L18), consistent with the exposed loop environment. Attention head L20:15 writes strongly (3.14 proj) from local context, while L18 features show moderate projections (F18:2075 at 18.3) encoding positional and secondary structure context.
perception_phase.context_character: By L23, the representation encodes an exposed loop position with polar/charged character, adjacent to charged residues (K48, E51) in a flexible region. The 4 structural contacts and minimal co-evolutionary signal (only 1 coupled position) indicate a surface-exposed site without strong functional constraints.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 4 residues within 8Å, suggesting surface exposure rather than buried core
Co-evolutionary signal: 1 coupled position, indicating weak functional constraint
Local sequence reading: L20:15 attention head (3.14 proj) reads adjacent charged residues K48 and E51
L18 features: F18:2075 (18.3 proj) and F18:4591 (16.0 proj) encode loop/turn preferences

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24 when D overtakes T (20% vs 36%), marking the transition from context assembly to amino-acid-specific prediction. D-specific MLP neurons activate strongly in L25-33: N25:2311 (0.75 proj), N27:2543 (0.84 proj), N31:2506 (1.22 proj), and N32:1334 (1.14 proj). The final surge from 49% at L29 to 88% at L33 is driven by massive feature projections (F33:3227 at 116.5, F33:8277 at 98.1) and MLP contributions (L33 MLP adds 8.1 to D logit). N asparagine remains the runner-up at 8.4%, reflecting the similar size and polarity but lacking the negative charge.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from encoding 'polar loop position' to activating D-specific prediction channels. T leads at L23 (36%), but L24 features (F24:217 at 31.7 proj, F24:2079 at 29.4 proj) and MLP neurons (N24:2854 at 0.58 proj for D) begin differentiating acidic from polar-uncharged. The lead change at L24 marks when the model commits to the acidic identity.

candidates.narrative: D emerges as the clear winner at L24 (20%) and accelerates through the decision phase, reaching 49% at L29 and peaking at 91% at L30. The prediction is driven by highly specific MLP neurons: N31:2506 projects 1.22 toward D (also votes for P and W, suggesting it encodes exposed acidic positions), N32:1334 projects 1.14 (voting equally for H, D, E—a general acidic channel). The final layers deploy massive prediction features: F33:3227 (MLP, 116.5 proj) and F33:8277 (MLP, 98.1 proj) lock in the aspartate identity with high confidence.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L24, dominant by L29, peaks at L30 (91%)
key_evidence: N31:2506 (1.22 proj) — D-specific neuron, also votes P/W
F33:3227 (MLP, 116.5 proj) — dominant D prediction feature
F33:8277 (MLP, 98.1 proj) — secondary D prediction feature

candidates.narrative: N asparagine maintains steady support as the polar alternative to D, peaking at 17% at L24 before settling at 8.4% final. It shares D's small size and polar character but lacks the negative charge. N receives support from neurons that vote for both: N13:4034 (0.20 proj for N, 0.20 for D), suggesting the model recognizes the structural similarity. The model ultimately rejects N in favor of D based on the charged local context (adjacent K48, E51) that favors acidic over neutral polar.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L24 (17%), declines to 8.4% by L33
key_evidence: N13:4034 (0.20 proj for both N and D) — encodes small polar character
Shares structural profile with D but lacks charge
Loses to D as acidic-specific features dominate L30-33

candidates.narrative: S serine leads the logit lens at L0 (23%) and maintains 13-14% through L14-23, but this reflects the representation's polar/small character in the perception phase, not a model prediction. The S signal comes from reading the local sequence context—S appears at position 57 nearby. As the model assembles more structural context and activates acidic-specific features in L24+, S collapses to 0.66% as the representation shifts from 'generic polar' to 'specifically acidic.'
candidates.key_layers: Leads L0-1 (23%), holds 13-14% through L23, collapses by L33
key_evidence: L0-23: representation consistent with small polar residues
Erased by acidic-specific features in decision phase

candidates.narrative: T threonine emerges as the logit-lens leader through L5-23, peaking at 36% at L24, reflecting the representation's polar/hydroxyl character during context assembly. This is not a prediction but rather the model encoding 'exposed polar position with hydrogen bonding capability.' The lead change at L24 when D overtakes T marks the transition from perception to decision—when the model shifts from encoding 'what kind of position is this' to 'which specific amino acid.' T receives votes from neurons encoding polar character but loses decisively as D-specific channels activate.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L5-23, peaks at L24 (36%), loses lead at L24
key_evidence: Lead change at L24 marks perception→decision transition
Loses as D-specific neurons (N27:2543, N31:2506) activate

candidates.narrative: E glutamate, the longer acidic alternative to D, maintains low but persistent support (1-6%) throughout, peaking at 6.6% at L32. It receives votes from acidic-general neurons (N32:1334 votes 1.10 for E vs 1.14 for D), but the model ultimately favors D's shorter sidechain for this position. The E vs D discrimination happens late (L30-33) and is subtle, suggesting the model uses fine-grained structural context to select the appropriate acidic sidechain length.
key_evidence: N32:1334 votes for both E (1.10) and D (1.14) — acidic channel
Model discriminates D vs E based on sidechain length
Late-phase competition resolved by structural fit

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from small polar (S) to positively charged (K peaks at 36% at L8) as the model reads adjacent K48 through local attention. This is not a prediction but reflects the model encoding the charged local environment. The K signal comes from structural reading—attention heads are gathering information about the charged neighbors that will later inform the acidic prediction.

The critical perception→decision transition. At L23, T leads at 36% with the representation encoding 'polar loop position.' At L24, D overtakes T (20% vs 36% declining) as D-specific prediction features activate (F24:217 at 31.7 proj, F24:2079 at 29.4 proj). MLP L25 contributes 5.56 net toward D, with N25:2311 (0.75 proj) and N25:3425 (0.81 proj) casting strong D votes. This is when the model commits to the acidic identity.

The final decision surge. D jumps from 49% at L29 to 91% at L30 (peak), driven by massive MLP contributions: L30 MLP erases 4.82 (velocity event), but L31 adds 5.35 and L32 adds 8.03. Key neurons fire: N30:1750 (0.74 proj), N31:2506 (1.22 proj), N32:1334 (1.14 proj). L33 deploys the strongest prediction features: F33:3227 (116.5 proj) and F33:8277 (98.1 proj) lock in D with 88% confidence. The L30 dip reflects competition with E (peaks at 6.6% at L32) before D-specific channels dominate.

deep_dives.label: Local attention L18-20
deep_dives.caption: L20:15 writes 3.14 proj from local context (99% local attention), reading adjacent charged residues K48 and E51. This establishes the charged environment that will later favor acidic residues. L18 heads show moderate structural reading (2-4% structural attention).

deep_dives.label: SAE features L18-24
deep_dives.caption: L18 features (F18:2075 at 18.3, F18:4591 at 16.0) encode loop/turn context. At L24, D-specific prediction channels emerge: F24:217 (31.7 proj) and F24:2079 (29.4 proj) mark the transition from context encoding to amino-acid prediction.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L25-27
deep_dives.caption: L25 contributes 5.56 net toward D with N25:2311 (0.75 proj) and N25:3425 (0.81 proj) activating. L27 neurons show strong D-specific voting: N27:2543 (0.84 proj) and N27:4903 (0.76 proj). This is where the model begins committing to aspartate over other polar residues.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L31-32
deep_dives.caption: The decisive neurons. N31:2506 projects 1.22 toward D (strongest single neuron), also voting for P/W (exposed position signature). N32:1334 projects 1.14 toward D and votes equally for H/D/E—a general acidic channel. L31 contributes 5.35 net, L32 contributes 8.03 net.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction features L33
deep_dives.caption: F33:3227 (MLP, 116.5 proj) and F33:8277 (MLP, 98.1 proj) are the dominant D prediction features, with projections 10-20× larger than any other layer. These lock in the final 88% confidence. F33:4166 (attn, 106.0 proj) and F33:326 (attn, 103.7 proj) provide additional support.

deep_dives.label: Velocity events L29-33
deep_dives.caption: L29 erases 4.91 (both attn and MLP), L30 erases 4.82 (MLP-driven), but L31 adds 5.35, L32 adds 5.98, and L33 adds 20.75 (MLP contributes 8.1). This oscillation reflects competition between D and E before D-specific channels dominate.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts D by assembling a representation of an exposed, charged loop position through L1-23, then activating D-specific prediction channels in L24-33. The strongest evidence comes from the convergence of highly specific MLP neurons (N31:2506 at 1.22 proj, N32:1334 at 1.14 proj) and massive prediction features (F33:3227 at 116.5 proj) that encode aspartate identity. The model successfully discriminates D from the similar N (polar but uncharged) and E (acidic but longer sidechain) based on the local charged context (K48, E51) and structural constraints of the exposed loop environment.
